{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640123"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:12:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:12:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17804"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17804"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.05,0.05,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10518"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72440"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10518"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57910"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7579"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24556"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72440"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hypodermis is the deepest layer of the integumentary system, lying beneath the dermis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary composition of the hypodermis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adipose tissue and loose connective tissue","Dense irregular connective tissue","Keratinised epithelial cells","Stratified squamous epithelium","Smooth muscle and elastin fibres"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hypodermis (subcutaneous tissue) is primarily composed of \u003Cstrong\u003Eadipose tissue and loose connective tissue\u003C/strong\u003E. This composition allows it to serve multiple functions including energy storage, thermal insulation, and mechanical protection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDense irregular connective tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of the dermis, where it provides strength and elasticity to the skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeratinised epithelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E are found in the stratum corneum of the epidermis, where they form a protective barrier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStratified squamous epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E forms the epidermis, the outermost layer of skin, providing protection against environmental damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmooth muscle and elastin fibres\u003C/strong\u003E are minor components, but do not represent the primary composition of the hypodermis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe hypodermis connects the skin to underlying fascia and contains blood vessels, nerves, and in some areas, hair follicle roots. Its loose structure allows for sliding movement of the skin over deeper tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The hypodermis (subcutaneous tissue) is primarily composed of adipose tissue and loose connective tissue.","The hypodermis connects the dermis to underlying fascia and muscle.","The hypodermis serves important functions in energy storage, insulation, and cushioning."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57910"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17804"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57910"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T20:43:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T20:44:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10518"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72440"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4932"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Skin and Associated Structures","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23